raced, classed, and gendered, and she exposes the moral core of this self and its seemingly paradoxical necessity to the Other. The construction of white female subjectivity is thereby revealed as contingent on notions of goodness and Othering, played out against, and constituted by, the backdrop of the NorthSouth binary, in which Canada’s national narrative situates us as the “good guys” of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspects. 0aImperialism. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aWomen in developmentzDeveloping countries. 0aWomen, WhitexRace identity. 0aWomen, WhitezDeveloping countries. 4aPolitical Science: African Politics. 4aSocial Science: Development Studies. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458098940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554580989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554580989/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles